Andy Kriger writes:
&gt; 
&gt; I want to load a text file that contains data to test. Currently, I
&gt; have static ArrayLists in my TestCase class. In the setUp method, I
&gt; check if those ArrayLists are null, and if they are, load the test
&gt; data. So, I only load the test data once but it seems messy to have
&gt; test data loaded for the whole suite in a method intended to setup a
&gt; single test method. I guess this data loading can be moved to the
&gt; suite() method?

As the suite() method only gets invoked once per test class, this would be a
place you could do it. If you do so, you&#39;ll have to manage the test-suite
yourself, however; the automatic discovery of tests via reflection will no
longer work.

&gt; However, I still have to hardcode the name of the data file. The
&gt; TestCase class has a main method and I tried passing the test file
&gt; name as an argument to that however that simply runs TestRunner
&gt; which creates a new instance of the TestCase and undoes my data
&gt; loading. Is there a way to pass the name of the data file as an 
&gt; argument to TestRunner so it can be loaded when TestRunner calls
&gt; suite()?

Not in this version.

&gt; If not, I guess I&#39;m looking for a setUp method for suites as well as
&gt; test methods.

We implemented such a utility at my last place of employment. In hindsight,
while it was fun and interesting, I consider the solution we used as
overkill (but then, we had a lot of time on our hands).

What I&#39;d suggest, with the benefit of hindsight, is a Singleton-like
pattern. Provide a utility class (possibly an inner class of the test class)
which provides static methods for obtaining your data. The first time that
the methods are called (or via a static initialisor, if you prefer), read
your data in, and cache it for future requests.

If you are worried about hard-coding the name of the data file, don&#39;t be;
for your automated tests, you&#39;ll want the data in a known location. If you
want some configurability over the test, you can always store the location
of the data file in a properties file.

If you&#39;re going to be using a known location for your automated test, but
you want to be able to override it (say, you&#39;ve got a data file that
reproduces a problem and you want to look into it), I&#39;d suggest writing a
main() method in your test class that configures the Singleton object. If
you invoke the test case manually, you&#39;ll be able to provide the location.
If you invoke it via JUnit or via another suite(), you won&#39;t.

Robert.

